<dl id="n10078a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10078a">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10078a"> 78(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pugilise <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10078a"><li>FW 426.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/lexpD.htm#n10078a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/l39pD.htm#n10078a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10078a">MS BL 47482b-44</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:089 <a name="pA3d" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pD3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/p/pd3d.htm#n10078a">Draft: III&sect;1D.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Nous savons que les lettres appel&eacute;es epistol&aelig; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> &eacute;taient &eacute;crites ordinairement sur des tablettes, tabul&aelig; ou tabell&aelig;, recouvertes de cire blanche ou color&eacute;e. On y gravait les lettres avec un poin&ccedil;on, stylus <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>. Le poin&ccedil;on &eacute;tait enferm&eacute; dans un &eacute;tui et servait d&apos;arme au besoin: on l&apos;appelait quelquefois pugillus (petit poignard) et les tablettes <mark>pugillares</mark>. <font color="green">[We know that the letters called epistol&aelig; [&hellip;]</font> were usually written on tablets, tabul&aelig; or tabell&aelig;, that were covered in white or coloured wax. Letters were carved with a needle, stylus <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>. The needle was shut up in a case and could be used as a weapon when needed. It was sometimes called pugillus (little dagger) and the tablets pugillares.] <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 47</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
